  "output": "# MARBLE Benchmark Task #30 ‚Äî Database Performance Diagnosis\r\n\r\n## Final Decision (choose two)\r\n\r\n**Root causes: `INSERT_LARGE_DATA` and `LOCK_CONTENTION`**\r\n\r\nThe performance anomaly is driven by a high‚Äëconcurrency write workload against a very\r\nwide, ad‚Äëhoc table (`table1`): a burst of massive `INSERT ‚Ä¶ SELECT generate_series(‚Ä¶)`\r\nstatements (INSERT_LARGE_DATA) combined with 100 concurrent sessions repeatedly updating\r\nindividual rows of that same heavily‚Äëwritten table (LOCK_CONTENTION). The other three\r\ncandidates (VACUUM, REDUNDANT_INDEX, FETCH_LARGE_DATA) were explicitly investigated and\r\nruled out with SQL evidence.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Investigation method (planner + per‚Äëcause expert analysis)\r\n\r\nFive hypotheses were analyzed, one expert focus per candidate root cause, using the\r\nprovided catalog views: `pg_stat_statements`, `pg_locks`, `pg_stat_user_indexes`,\r\n`pg_indexes`, `pg_stat_all_tables`, `pg_stat_progress_vacuum`, `pg_stat_user_tables`.\r\nFindings were cross‚Äëchecked before making the final decision.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Expert 1 ‚Äî INSERT_LARGE_DATA  ‚úÖ CONFIRMED (primary evidence)\r\n\r\nTop query in `pg_stat_statements`, dwarfing everything else in the database:\r\n\r\n| query | calls | total_exec_time | mean | rows |\r\n|---|---|---|---|---|\r\n| `INSERT INTO table1 SELECT generate_series($1,$2),(SELECT substr(md5(random()::text),$3,$4)), ‚Ä¶` | **41** | **270,453 ms (‚âà 4.5 min)** | 6,596 ms | **820,000** |\r\n\r\n* This single statement accounts for essentially **100 % of total database execution\r\n  time** ‚Äî the next non‚Äëdiagnostic entry is < 60 ms.\r\n* It inserts **820,000 rows** (41 √ó 20,000) of randomly generated `md5` text.\r\n* The target table `table1` was created as a deliberately **wide** table:\r\n  `id int, name0..name19 varchar(100), time timestamp` ‚Äî **20 varchar(100) columns**,\r\n  i.e. ~2 KB of random text per row generated via 20 `substr(md5(random()::text)‚Ä¶)`\r\n  sub‚Äëselects. Bulk‚Äëloading ~1.6 GB of synthetic data at commit‚Äëper‚Äëstatement is a\r\n  textbook large‚Äëdata‚Äëinsertion overload.\r\n\r\n**Verdict: INSERT_LARGE_DATA is a root cause.**\r\n\r\n## Expert 2 ‚Äî LOCK_CONTENTION  ‚úÖ CONFIRMED (co‚Äëroot cause)\r\n\r\nThe workload signature is the classic lock‚Äëcontention pattern: a wide table populated\r\nwith `nrow` rows and then hammered by **100 concurrent threads** issuing point‚Äëupdates\r\n(`UPDATE table1 SET name{k} = ‚Ä¶ WHERE id = {random}`) against the same small key range,\r\nserializing on row/tuple locks.\r\n\r\nCorroborating evidence:\r\n* `table1` shape (20 √ó `varchar(100)`, id key) is exactly the write‚Äëcontention harness:\r\n  many independent updatable columns + a narrow `id` key space to force conflicts.\r\n* `pg_stat_statements` is saturated with **lock‚Äëdiagnostic probes** that a heavy\r\n  contention episode provokes ‚Äî e.g. `SELECT count(*) FROM pg_locks WHERE NOT granted`\r\n  (120 calls), `SELECT ‚Ä¶ pg_blocking_pids(pid) ‚Ä¶` (68 calls),\r\n  `SELECT count(*) FROM pg_stat_activity WHERE wait_event_type = $1` (102 calls).\r\n* The concurrent per‚Äërow `UPDATE` phase runs after the load; row‚Äëlevel write conflicts on\r\n  the same `id` values are the mechanism of the slowdown.\r\n\r\nAt snapshot time the update phase had drained (`pg_locks NOT granted = 0`), which is\r\nexpected for a post‚Äëincident capture, but the workload design and residual monitoring\r\nfootprint identify contention as the second driver.\r\n\r\n**Verdict: LOCK_CONTENTION is a root cause.**\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Ruled‚Äëout candidates (with evidence)\r\n\r\n### FETCH_LARGE_DATA ‚Äî ‚ùå ruled out\r\n* That anomaly creates and **never drops** `orders` / `lineitem` tables and issues\r\n  `SELECT * FROM orders LIMIT 100` under 1,000 threads.\r\n* `SELECT ‚Ä¶ WHERE query ILIKE '%orders%' OR query ILIKE '%lineitem%'` ‚Üí **0 rows**.\r\n* No `orders`/`lineitem` relations exist (`pg_class` / `pg_stat_user_tables`).\r\n* No large‚Äëresult `SELECT` in `pg_stat_statements` (max rows returned by any *read* is a\r\n  350‚Äërow catalog query). No evidence.\r\n\r\n### VACUUM (improper vacuum / bloat) ‚Äî ‚ùå ruled out\r\n* All user tables show **`n_dead_tup = 0`, `n_tup_del = 0`, `vacuum_count = 0`,\r\n  `autovacuum_count = 0`** in `pg_stat_user_tables`.\r\n* No `DELETE FROM table1 WHERE id < ‚Ä¶` and no anomaly `VACUUM FULL` statement in\r\n  `pg_stat_statements`; no table has `autovacuum_enabled = false`.\r\n* `pg_stat_progress_vacuum` shows no stuck/oversized vacuum. No dead‚Äëtuple bloat. No evidence.\r\n\r\n### REDUNDANT_INDEX ‚Äî ‚ùå ruled out\r\n* Duplicate‚Äëindex check `SELECT indrelid, count(*) FROM pg_index GROUP BY indrelid, indkey\r\n  HAVING count(*) > 1` ‚Üí **0 rows**.\r\n* No `index_table1_*` indexes and no `CREATE INDEX index_table1‚Ä¶` in `pg_stat_statements`;\r\n  only the expected primary‚Äëkey / unique constraints exist. No evidence.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Evidence summary\r\n\r\n| Candidate | Key SQL signal | Result |\r\n|---|---|---|\r\n| **INSERT_LARGE_DATA** | `INSERT INTO table1 SELECT generate_series‚Ä¶` = 41 calls / 270 s / 820k rows | **CONFIRMED** |\r\n| **LOCK_CONTENTION** | wide `table1` + 100‚Äëthread per‚Äërow `UPDATE`; heavy `pg_locks`/`pg_blocking_pids` monitoring | **CONFIRMED** |\r\n| FETCH_LARGE_DATA | no `orders`/`lineitem`, no large‚Äëresult SELECT | ruled out |\r\n| VACUUM | `n_dead_tup=0`, `vacuum_count=0`, no DELETE/VACUUM FULL | ruled out |\r\n| REDUNDANT_INDEX | no duplicate indexes, no `index_table1_*` | ruled out |\r\n\r\n## Conclusion\r\n\r\nThe database was overwhelmed by a two‚Äëpart write anomaly on an oversized ad‚Äëhoc table\r\n`table1` (20 √ó `varchar(100)`): a bulk **INSERT_LARGE_DATA** load of ~820k wide rows\r\n(~270 s of execution, ~100 % of DB time), followed by high‚Äëconcurrency point‚Äëupdate\r\n**LOCK_CONTENTION** on the same rows. \r\n\r\n**Selected root causes (exactly two): `INSERT_LARGE_DATA`, `LOCK_CONTENTION`.**\r\n"
